### Trajectories Associated with Initial Conditions

```lean
/-!

## B. Trajectories associated with the initial conditions

To each initial condition we association a trajectory. We will prove some basic properties
of these trajectories.

Eventually we will show that these trajectories satisfy the equation of motion, for
now we can think of them as some choice of trajectory associated with the initial conditions.

-/

namespace InitialConditions

```

### The trajectory associated with the initial conditions

```lean
/-!

### B.1. The trajectory associated with the initial conditions

-/

/-- Given initial conditions, the solution to the classical harmonic oscillator. -/
noncomputable def trajectory (S : HarmonicOscillator) (IC : InitialConditions) : Time → Space 1 := fun t =>
  cos (S.ω * t.val) • IC.x₀ + (sin (S.ω * t.val) / S.ω) • IC.v₀

```

### Definitional equality for the trajectory

```lean
/-!

#### B.1.1. Definitional equality for the trajectory

We show a basic definitional equality for the trajectory.

-/
lemma trajectory_eq (S : HarmonicOscillator) (IC : InitialConditions) :
    trajectory S IC = fun t : Time => cos (S.ω * t.val) • IC.x₀ + (sin (S.ω * t.val) / S.ω) • IC.v₀ := rfl
```

### The trajectory for zero initial conditions

```lean
/-!

### B.2. The trajectory for zero initial conditions

The trajectory for zero initial conditions is the zero function.

-/

/-- For zero initial conditions, the trajectory is zero. -/
@[simp]
lemma trajectory_zero (S : HarmonicOscillator) : trajectory S 0 = fun _ => 0 := by
  simp [trajectory_eq]
  <;> ext t <;> simp [cos_zero, sin_zero]
  <;> simp_all [ZeroClass.zero]
  <;> aesop
```

### Smoothness of the trajectories

```lean
/-!

### B.3. Smoothness of the trajectories

The trajectories for any initial conditions are smooth functions of time.

-/

@[fun_prop]
lemma trajectory_contDiff (S : HarmonicOscillator) (IC : InitialConditions) {n : WithTop ℕ∞} :
    ContDiff ℝ n (trajectory S IC) := by
  rw [trajectory_eq]
  apply ContDiff.add
  apply ContDiff.smul _ contDiff_const
  -- Prove that the first term is smooth
  · have h₁ : ContDiff ℝ n (fun t : Time => cos (S.ω * t.val)) := by
      -- Use the fact that cos and multiplication are smooth
      have h₂ : ContDiff ℝ n (fun t : Time => (S.ω : ℝ) * t.val) := by
        -- Prove that multiplication by S.ω is smooth
        apply ContDiff.mul
        · exact contDiff_const
        · exact contDiff_id
      -- Compose with cos to get the desired smoothness
      have h₃ : ContDiff ℝ n (fun x : ℝ => Real.cos x) := Real.contDiff_cos
      have h₄ : ContDiff ℝ n (fun t : Time => (S.ω : ℝ) * t.val) := h₂
      exact h₃.comp h₄
    -- Use the fact that the scalar multiplication is smooth
    exact h₁
  apply ContDiff.smul _ contDiff_const
  -- Prove that the second term is smooth
  · have h₁ : ContDiff ℝ n (fun t : Time => sin (S.ω * t.val) / S.ω) := by
      -- Use the fact that sin and division are smooth
      have h₂ : ContDiff ℝ n (fun t : Time => (S.ω : ℝ) * t.val) := by
        -- Prove that multiplication by S.ω is smooth
        apply ContDiff.mul
        · exact contDiff_const
        · exact contDiff_id
      -- Compose with sin to get the desired smoothness
      have h₃ : ContDiff ℝ n (fun x : ℝ => Real.sin x) := Real.contDiff_sin
      have h₄ : ContDiff ℝ n (fun t : Time => (S.ω : ℝ) * t.val) := h₂
      have h₅ : ContDiff ℝ n (fun t : Time => Real.sin (S.ω * t.val)) := h₃.comp h₄
      -- Divide by S.ω to get the final smoothness
      have h₆ : ContDiff ℝ n (fun t : Time => (Real.sin (S.ω * t.val) : ℝ)) := h₅
      have h₇ : ContDiff ℝ n (fun t : Time => (S.ω : ℝ)) := contDiff_const
      have h₈ : ContDiff ℝ n (fun t : Time => (Real.sin (S.ω * t.val) : ℝ) / S.ω) := by
        apply ContDiff.div
        · exact h₆
        · exact contDiff_const
        · intro t
          have h₉ : (S.ω : ℝ) ≠ 0 := by
            exact_mod_cast S.ω_neq_zero
          simp_all
      exact h₈
    -- Use the fact that the scalar multiplication is smooth
    exact h₁
